    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-09T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-09T18:00:00-05:00" n="828"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d828">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6–945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-09T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 9, 1945—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>889. Personal for the Ambassador. I have seen a copy of your telegram of June 6
                    to Secretary Morgenthau in reply to his message giving you background
                    information on the supply of gold to China. I feel that you should know that
                    State, Treasury and other interested agencies reached a decision on this matter
                    only after full consideration of all factors involved and on the basis of all
                    available information. If there is a shortcoming it arises out of the oversight
                    of the Department in not sending to you accounts of the progress of the
                    conversations held.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
